She flipped to a blank page and wrote down the date. Then, she wrote below the date: "5/11/648-12/13/648".
"Looking back on the past?" Avery asked, looking at the old notebook. Carly nodded. "Do you think they'd let you go out for Christmas? There are only a few days left until Christmas."
Carly tapped twice on the lantern, indicating "No." As Avery had expected. The Ice King never allowed Carly to go outside, because in his eyes, Carly was "a flaw." Carly was born deaf and was the only girl in her family, while all the other children were boys.
Avery was also like that, in their own unique way. When Avery publicly appeared as a non-binary person, the world seemed to change as well. As a punishment for being different, they were mostly forced to work alone for most of the time.
They were also forced to be the princess's servant. However, they didn't mind, because they had a friend.
"Your birthday is coming up, right?" Avery asked, remembering that in a few days it would be the princess's birthday. Carly nodded, a flicker of sadness passing through her pale blue eyes.
"Do you want to celebrate?" they asked, recalling how Carly had answered this question last time.
No. Carly tapped on the table. Avery knew this was a difficult topic for Carly to bring up. On that day, she was imprisoned in this room, while her mother was executed. When it happened, Avery was still an infant, but they remembered the anger of the servants and citizens at the time. They heard that Queen Alvin was a good queen, and could miraculously predict future events.
"Then... what do you want to do?" they asked. Carly looked up at them, excited. She handed Avery a piece of paper. However, when he looked down at it...
6 inches X 6 inches canvas
White, varying shades of blue paint
Six brushes of different sizes
Easel
"Are you asking me to get these things for you?" Avery turned to the silent princess, who was constantly tapping and her ponytail swaying back and forth. "Right?" When they saw the usually quiet princess so enthusiastic about something, they couldn't help but giggle. This was the first time she wanted something outside of her room, and it had nothing to do with books.
"Okay! See you later?" Avery said, standing up and walking through the mess of papers and notebooks.
Carly nodded and continued to curl up in the thick blanket, recalling her memories.
They walked out of the room, feeling relieved that the princess was finally willing to try something new and had made some requests beyond her capabilities (such as paints).
They walked through the hall again, trying not to pay attention to the maids' whispers.
"I heard she's possessed by Queen Alvin, so she always goes to that room."
"I heard she eats children in that room."
"Does she look like a man? Is that normal?"
They couldn't take hearing these words anymore and had to cover their ears. They went to the royal painter's room, which was in the east wing, the second door on the left.
Avery arrived at that door, which was as ornately decorated as Carly's door. A white dragon was painted on the door, one of the six original dragons, said to be the one that created the Frost Kingdom. It was no surprise that the painter, who loved history, had painted the white dragon on the door.
They opened the door, expecting everything to be as usual. For example, there were paints everywhere, pencils and papers scattered around, and easels covered every inch of the walls. Unexpectedly, the scene inside the room was completely different. The room was neat, with a red velvet backdrop and a chair. Sitting on the chair was Crown Prince Aquilo, who was painting a portrait.
"Ah, good morning, Avery! Want to see a portrait of your future king?" Aquilo asked, winking at Avery.
"Sorry, Prince," they replied, beginning to look around for the art supplies Princess Carly wanted. "I was just here to get some art supplies."
"Little darling, leaving so soon?" Aquilo asked, "But I still wanted to see you!"
"I don't want to," Avery found the art supplies on the list and placed them in a box. "And I'm not a girl."
The prince dismissed this. "Oh, darling, you know this is just a phase! Once you grow up, it'll be fine!" he mumbled.
"I have to go," they said, suddenly feeling uncomfortable as the prince continued talking. They recalled all the negative comments people had made about their gender identity. I really want to get away from him.
"Leaving so soon?" The prince instantly appeared at the door, ignoring the royal painter's shouts.
"This is not the behavior of a future king!" They said sternly.
"No one will know. People won't believe you, and if that painter still values his life, he won't say anything either." The prince glanced back at the painter and then leaned in close to Avery. "What do you think of a date?" They shivered in fear. Of course, they had heard many threats before, but none of them had come from the prince, let alone from this future king.
"Do you know what the word 'no' means?" They scolded, shoving the prince aside.
"No," Aquilo replied with a smile. This prince, who could get whatever he wanted, of course didn't know what the word "no" meant.
Avery rolled their eyes. "Why are there so many people, and you specifically want to go on a date with me? How many suitors do you have? A hundred?"
He interrupted with a smile: "To be exact, over five hundred." He flicked his hair, swaying in the cold wind.
"See? Why me? I'm a disaster in the palace." They crossed their arms.
"You're the most beautiful girl I've ever seen." Aquilo placed a finger under Avery's chin, forcing Avery to look up at him.
